    <div class="container">

      <h2>Why AC Failure in Laveen Is Dangerous — and Why Help Is Hard to Find</h2>
      <p>
        Laveen sits at the southwestern edge of Phoenix, where the urban heat island begins to
        give way to open desert terrain. Summer temperatures in Laveen regularly reach 112–116°F
        on peak days — comparable to Buckeye and the broader West Valley. On still days with
        limited wind, Laveen can be among the hottest areas of the metro. A home without
        functioning air conditioning here can reach 100°F internally within a couple of hours
        on a peak summer afternoon.
      </p>
      <p>
        Maricopa County's heat death statistics are unambiguous: the county records more
        heat-related deaths than any other county in the country, and they occur across every
        part of the metro — not just in the urban core. Laveen residents face the same risk
        as anyone else in the Valley when AC fails.
      </p>
      <p>
        What makes Laveen's situation particularly challenging is the HVAC service gap.
        Most large HVAC companies in the Phoenix metro are based east of the 51 or in the
        central city. Coming to Laveen means a 35–45 minute drive each way, which gets
        priced into service calls or deprioritized entirely during busy summer weeks. Altered
