        drive from Buckeye, and we treat Laveen calls exactly as we treat calls from anywhere
        else in our service area.
      </p>

      <div class="content-two-col" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">
        <div>
          <h2>New Construction, Dobbins Road, and the Builder-Grade AC Problem</h2>
          <p>
            Laveen has transformed rapidly over the past decade from a semi-rural agricultural
            community into one of Phoenix's most active residential growth areas. New subdivisions
            have spread along Dobbins Road, 35th Avenue, 51st Avenue, and into the foothills
            approaching South Mountain, bringing tens of thousands of new residents into homes
            built under the same production-speed pressures that produce builder-grade HVAC
            problems throughout the West Valley.
          </p>
          <p>
            The pattern is consistent: a family moves into a new Laveen home in October or
            November, experiences their first mild Arizona winter, and then hits June. The
            system runs from 7 a.m. to midnight. By the second week of July, the home can't
            hold 78°F when it's 115°F outside. John Rigo has diagnosed this exact situation
            dozens of times — sometimes it is a refrigerant undercharge from a quick installation,
            sometimes it is a genuinely undersized system, sometimes it is a dirty condenser
            coil that nobody ever told the homeowner to clean.
          </p>
          <p>
            South Mountain's proximity creates some unique microclimate effects in Laveen —
            the mountain blocks certain wind patterns and creates thermal conditions that can
            differ from central Phoenix. Homes on the northern slopes facing the mountain get
            different sun exposure than homes on the flat. AC system sizing that ignores
            these local factors can produce underperformance even if the equipment would be
            adequate elsewhere.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
